post_text:
Updated mask requirement (8/17/2020) released by the Pennsylvania Department of Health and Pennsylvania Department of Education:

PDE in cooperation with DOH announced yesterday, the requirement of all students to wear facial coverings at all times, while in school. This is an update from the prior order that allowed students to not wear masks if six-feet of social distancing was able to be achieved.

Those students that meet medical criteria to not wear a mask will be excused from this change.

The change is based on the American Academy of Pediatrics' updated guidance that strongly recommends children age two and older should wear facial coverings at all times to mitigate the spread of COVID-19.

West Perry School District will keep you posted on any new developments as they unfold.

post_text:
Do you know which is better, hand sanitizer or soap and water? The simple answer is...it depends. Although hand sanitizer, if used correctly, is effective in killing bacteria and viruses, soap and water kills the germs and removes all the grime hiding other germs. However, soap and clean water is not always accessible. That is when hand sanitizer comes to the rescue. It is easy to stow and carry with you wherever to go. Throwing ball in the park? Take your hand sanitizer to use before getting back in the car but don’t forget to wash your hands when you get home. Stay safe.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x7KKkElpyKQ&feature=youtu.be

How to help prevent the spread of COVID-19:

Much is unknown about how the virus that causes COVID-19 spreads. We believe it spreads mostly from person to person through respiratory droplets produced when someone who is sick coughs or sneezes.

You can help prevent the spread of respiratory illnesses like COVID-19 by following simple daily precautions.
Learn how to protect yourself from COVID-19: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/prevention.html

shared_text:
Carroll Elementary School
July 17 at 8:22 AM ·

Pre-K at Carroll for 2020 - 2021. Three spots still remain open!

As a PreK Counts recipient, West Perry School District operates pre-kindergarten classrooms in each of the elementary schools. Classes of seventeen students are led by a teacher and paraprofessional. Students attend for 5.5 hours, 180 days each year.
Students are selected from applications during the enrollment process each Spring. Priority is given to students based on family income and other risk factors. Transportation is provided.

Applications are being accepted for the 2020-2021 school year. You can print the application and mail it to, or drop it off at the District Office. You can also call the District Office and have a copy mailed to you. The District Office is located at 2606 Shermans Valley Rd, Elliottsburg, PA 17024. The phone number is 717-789-3934. Access the PreK application by going to the WPSD Homepage...Go to the DISTRICT tab, Go to CURRICULUM & INSTRUCTION, and click on PreK. There is a link on that page to access the application.

On Friday, April 17th, the WPSD will be participating in the "Be Light" campaign. This is to honor the graduating class of 2020, healthcare workers, first responders, and all who are on the front line fighting the COVID-19 Pandemic. The lights will be turned on for 20 minutes at 8:20pm (20:20 military time) and the scoreboard will read a score of 20-20 with a down and distance of 4th and 19 to signify that we will overcome COVID-19.

Our hope is to provide a drive-thru opportunity to our seniors, families, and community members to give them a few minutes of light and hope that these tough times are almost over. Families who do happen to drive by the stadium are reminded that this is intended to be a drive-thru and should not get out of their vehicles.

Please enter the campus between the HS and MS and exit near the baseball field. Pictures of the stadium will also be shared on soci meal media and the West Perry School District website.

Thank you for your support and understanding during this uncertain time!
Dave Zula

post_text: STEM Camp in West Perry SD is off to an exceptional start! Check out our photo journal which documents a high-degree of interest and engagement in STEM-related camp activity. Campers have designed, built, and tested a variety of products which include water bottle rockets, paper roller coasters, and lunar landing modules. VEX IQ systems are allowing us to program robots to do tasks and solve problems. Campers are using the Engineering Design Process Model to ask, imagine, plan, create, experiment, and improve their designs. Connecting math concepts to building gives campers authentic opportunities to apply those concepts and ideas to real-world scenarios. Campers are making predictions, collecting data, evaluating results, and reflecting on their learning. We are having fun and STEM-ing on!
text: STEM Camp in West Perry SD is off to an exceptional start! Check out our photo journal which documents a high-degree of interest and engagement in STEM-related camp activity. Campers have designed, built, and tested a variety of products which include water bottle rockets, paper roller coasters, and lunar landing modules. VEX IQ systems are allowing us to program robots to do tasks and solve problems. Campers are using the Engineering Design Process Model to ask, imagine, plan, create, experiment, and improve their designs. Connecting math concepts to building gives campers authentic opportunities to apply those concepts and ideas to real-world scenarios. Campers are making predictions, collecting data, evaluating results, and reflecting on their learning. We are having fun and STEM-ing on!
